# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: astrobiology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] However, further research cast doubt upon the planet's habitability.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Based on newer models of the habitable zone, the planet is likely too hot to be potentially habitable.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] In astronomical terms, the Gliese 581 system is relatively close to Earth, at 20.55 light-years (194 trillion kilometres; 121 trillion miles) in the direction of the constellation of Libra.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] This distance, along with the declination and right ascension coordinates, give its exact location in the Milky Way.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] The team released a paper of their findings dated 27 April 2007, published in the July 2007 journal *Astronomy & Astrophysics*.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] In the paper, they also announced the discovery of another planet in the system, Gliese 581d, with a minimum mass of 7.7 Earth masses and a semi-major axis of 0.25 astronomical units.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] The existence of Gliese 581c and its mass have been measured by the radial velocity method of detecting exoplanets.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] The mass of a planet is calculated by the small periodic movements around a common centre of mass between the host star Gliese 581 and its planets.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] When all planets are fitted with a Keplerian solution, the minimum mass of the planet is determined to be 5.5 Earth masses.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] The radial velocity method cannot by itself determine the true mass, but it cannot be very much larger than this or the system would be dynamically unstable.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Dynamical simulations of the Gliese 581 system which assume the orbits of the planets are coplanar indicate that the planets cannot exceed approximately 1.6 to 2 times their minimum masses or the planetary system would be unstable (this is primarily due to the interaction between planets e and b).
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] For Gliese 581c, the upper bound is 10.4 Earth masses.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] A 2024 study determined the inclination of the planet, allowing its true mass to be determined, which is about 30% greater than the minimum mass at about 6.8 Earth masses.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Since Gliese 581c has not been detected in transit, there are no measurements of its radius.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Furthermore, the radial velocity method used to detect it only puts a lower limit on the planet's mass, which means theoretical models of planetary radius and structure can only be of limited use.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] However, assuming a random orientation of the planet's orbit, the true mass is likely to be close to the measured minimum mass.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Assuming that the true mass is the minimum mass, the radius may be calculated using various models.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] For example, if Gliese 581c is a rocky planet with a large iron core, it should have a radius approximately 50% larger than that of Earth, according to Udry's team.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Gravity on such a planet's surface would be approximately 2.24 times as strong as on Earth.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] However, if Gliese 581c is an icy and/or watery planet, its radius would be less than 2 times that of Earth, even with a very large outer hydrosphere, according to density models compiled by Diana Valencia and her team for Gliese 876 d.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Gravity on the surface of such an icy and/or watery planet would be at least 1.25 times as strong as on Earth.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] They claim the real value of the radius may be anything between the two extremes calculated by density models outlined above.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] If the planet transits the star as seen from the direction of the Earth, the radius should be measurable, albeit with some uncertainty.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Unfortunately, measurements made with the Canadian-built MOST space telescope indicate that transits do not occur.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] The new research suggests that the rocky centres of super-Earths are unlikely to evolve into terrestrial rocky planets like the inner planets of the Solar System because they appear to hold onto their large atmospheres.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Rather than evolving to a planet composed mainly of rock with a thin atmosphere, the small rocky core remains engulfed by its large hydrogen-rich envelope.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Gliese 581c has an orbital period ("year") of 13 Earth days and its orbital radius is only about 7% that of the Earth, about 11 million km, while the Earth is 150 million km from the Sun.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Since the host star is smaller and colder than the Sun—and thus less luminous—this distance places the planet on the "warm" edge of the habitable zone around the star according to Udry's team.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] In any case, based on newer models of the habitable zone, the planet is likely too hot to be potentially habitable.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] A typical radius for an M0 star of Gliese 581's age and metallicity is 0.00128 AU, against the Sun's 0.00465 AU.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] This proximity means that the primary star should appear 3.75 times wider and 14 times larger in area for an observer on the planet's surface looking at the sky than the Sun appears to be from Earth's surface.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Because of its small separation from Gliese 581, the planet has been generally considered to always have one hemisphere facing the star (only day), and the other always facing away (only night), or in other words being tidally locked.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] The most recent orbital fit to the system, taking stellar activity into account indicates a nearly circular orbit, but older fits used an eccentricity between 0.10 and 0.22.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] If the orbit of the planet were eccentric, it would undergo violent tidal flexing.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Because tidal forces are stronger when the planet is close to the star, eccentric planets are expected to have a rotation period that is shorter than its orbital period, also called pseudo-synchronization.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] An example of this effect is seen in Mercury, which is tidally locked in a 3:2 resonance, completing three rotations every two orbits.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] In any case, even in the case of 1:1 tidal lock, the planet would undergo libration and the terminator would be alternatively lit and darkened during libration.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Models of the evolution of the planet's orbit over time suggest that heating resulting from this tidal locking may play a major role in the planet's geology.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Models proposed by scientists predict that tidal heating could yield a surface heat flux about three times greater than that of Jupiter's moon Io, which could result in major geological activity such as volcanoes and plate tectonics.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Using the measured stellar luminosity of Gliese 581 of 0.013 times that of the Sun, it is possible to calculate Gliese 581c's effective temperature, a.k.a. black body temperature, which probably differs from its surface temperature.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] However, the effective temperature and actual surface temperature can be very different due to the greenhouse properties of the planetary atmosphere.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] For example, Venus has an effective temperature of −41 °C (−42 °F), but a surface temperature of 464 °C (867 °F) (mainly due to a 96.5% carbon dioxide atmosphere), a difference of about 505 °C (910 °F).
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Studies of habitability (i.e. liquid water for extremophile forms of life) conclude that Gliese 581c is likely to suffer from a runaway greenhouse effect similar to that found on Venus and, as such, is highly unlikely to be habitable.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Nevertheless, this runaway greenhouse effect could be prevented by the presence of sufficient reflective cloud cover on the planet's day side.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Gliese 581c is likely to lie outside the habitable zone.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] No direct evidence has been found for water to be present, and it is probably not present in the liquid state.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Theoretical models predict that volatile compounds such as water and carbon dioxide, if present, might evaporate in the scorching heat of the sunward side, migrate to the cooler night side, and condense to form ice caps.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Over time, the entire atmosphere might freeze into ice caps on the night side of the planet.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] However, it remains unknown if water and/or carbon dioxide are even present on the surface of Gliese 581c.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Alternatively, an atmosphere large enough to be stable would circulate the heat more evenly, allowing for a wider habitable area on the surface.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] For example, although Venus has a small axial inclination, very little sunlight reaches the surface at the poles.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] A slow rotation rate approximately 117 times slower than Earth's produces prolonged days and nights.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Despite the uneven distribution of sunlight cast on Venus at any given time, polar areas and the night side of Venus are kept almost as hot as on the day side by globally circulating winds.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] A Message from Earth (AMFE) is a high-powered digital radio signal that was sent on 9 October 2008 towards Gliese 581c.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] The signal is a digital time capsule containing 501 messages that were selected through a competition on the social networking site Bebo.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] The message was sent using the RT-70 radar telescope of Ukraine's State Space Agency.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] The signal will reach the planet Gliese 581c in early 2029.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] More than half a million people including celebrities and politicians participated in the AMFE project, which was the world's first digital time capsule where the content was selected by the public.
[src:astrobiology/a-message-from-earth] Estonian singer Laura Põldvere sings poetically about the "beautiful far-away planet" in her song *581c*.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:astrobiology/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The **abundance of the chemical elements** is a measure of the occurrences of the chemical elements relative to all other elements in a given environment.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Abundance is measured in one of three ways: by *mass fraction* (in commercial contexts often called *weight fraction*), by *mole fraction* (fraction of atoms by numerical count, or sometimes fraction of molecules in gases), or by *volume fraction*.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Volume fraction is a common abundance measure in mixed gases such as planetary atmospheres, and is similar in value to molecular mole fraction for gas mixtures at relatively low densities and pressures, and ideal gas mixtures.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Most abundance values in this article are given as mass fractions.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The abundance of chemical elements in the universe is dominated by the large amounts of hydrogen and helium which were produced during Big Bang nucleosynthesis.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Remaining elements, making up only about 2% of the universe, were largely produced by supernova nucleosynthesis.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Elements with even atomic numbers are generally more common than their neighbors in the periodic table, due to their favorable energetics of formation, described by the Oddo–Harkins rule.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The abundance of elements in the Sun and outer planets is similar to that in the universe.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Due to solar heating, the elements of Earth and the inner rocky planets of the Solar System have undergone an additional depletion of volatile hydrogen, helium, neon, nitrogen, and carbon (which volatilizes as methane).
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The crust, mantle, and core of the Earth show evidence of chemical segregation plus some sequestration by density.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Lighter silicates of aluminium are found in the crust, with more magnesium silicate in the mantle, while metallic iron and nickel compose the core.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The abundance of elements in specialized environments, such as atmospheres, oceans, or the human body, are primarily a product of chemical interactions with the medium in which they reside.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Abundance of each element is expressed as a relative number.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Astronomy uses a logarithmic scale for abundance $\epsilon _{X}$ of element X relative to hydrogen, defined by $\epsilon _{X}\equiv \log(N_{X}/N_{H})+12.00$ for number density N ; $\epsilon _{H}=12.00$ on this scale.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Another scale is mass fraction or, equivalently, percent by mass.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] For example, the abundance of oxygen in pure water can be measured in two ways: the *mass fraction* is about 89%, because that is the fraction of water's mass which is oxygen.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] However, the *mole fraction* is about 33% because only 1 atom of 3 in water, H2O, is oxygen.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Changing the given environment to Jupiter's outer atmosphere, where hydrogen is diatomic while helium is not, changes the *molecular* mole fraction (fraction of total gas molecules), as well as the fraction of atmosphere by volume, of hydrogen to about 86%, and of helium to 13%.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Below Jupiter's outer atmosphere, volume fractions are significantly different from mole fractions due to high temperatures (ionization and disproportionation) and high density, where the ideal gas law is inapplicable.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Remaining elements, making up only about 2% of the universe, were largely produced by supernovae and certain red giant stars.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Lithium, beryllium, and boron, despite their low atomic number, are rare because, although they are produced by nuclear fusion, they are destroyed by other reactions in the stars.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Their natural occurrence is the result of cosmic ray spallation of carbon, nitrogen and oxygen in a type of nuclear fission reaction.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The elements from carbon to iron are relatively more abundant in the universe because of the ease of making them in supernova nucleosynthesis.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Elements of higher atomic numbers than iron (element 26) become progressively rarer in the universe, because they increasingly absorb stellar energy in their production.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Also, elements with even atomic numbers are generally more common than their neighbors in the periodic table, due to favorable energetics of formation (see Oddo–Harkins rule), and among the lightest nuclides helium through sulfur the most abundant isotopes of equal number of protons and neutrons.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Hydrogen is the most abundant element in the Universe; helium is second.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] All others are orders of magnitude less common.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] After this, the rank of abundance does not continue to correspond to the atomic number.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Oxygen has abundance rank 3, but atomic number 8.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] There are 80 known stable elements, and the lightest 16 comprise 99.9% of the ordinary matter of the universe.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The Segrè plot is initially linear because (aside from hydrogen) the vast majority of ordinary matter (99.4% in the Solar System) contains an equal number of protons and neutrons (Z=N).
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The abundance of the elements up to lithium is well predicted by the standard cosmological model, since they were mostly produced shortly (i.e., within a few hundred seconds) after the Big Bang, in a process known as Big Bang nucleosynthesis.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Heavier elements were mostly produced much later, in stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] In general, elements up to iron are made by large stars in the process of becoming supernovae, or by smaller stars in the process of dying.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Iron-56 is particularly common, since it is the most stable nuclide (in that it has the highest nuclear binding energy per nucleon) and can easily be "built up" from alpha particles (being a product of decay of radioactive nickel-56, ultimately made from 14 helium nuclei).
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Elements heavier than iron are made in energy-absorbing processes in large stars, and their abundance in the universe (and on Earth) generally decreases with increasing atomic number.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The table shows the ten most common elements in our galaxy (estimated spectroscopically), as measured in parts per million, by mass.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Nearby galaxies that have evolved along similar lines have a corresponding enrichment of elements heavier than hydrogen and helium.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The more distant galaxies are being viewed as they appeared in the past, so their abundances of elements appear closer to the primordial mixture.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Since physical laws and processes are apparently uniform throughout the universe, however, it is expected that these galaxies will likewise have evolved similar abundances of elements.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] As shown in the periodic table, the abundance of elements is in keeping with their origin.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Very abundant hydrogen and helium are products of the Big Bang.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The next three elements in the periodic table (lithium, beryllium, and boron) are rare, despite their low atomic number.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] They had little time to form in the Big Bang.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] They are produced in small quantities by nuclear fusion in dying stars or by breakup of heavier elements in interstellar dust, caused by cosmic ray spallation.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] In supernova stars, they are produced by nuclear fusion, but then destroyed by other reactions.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Heavier elements, beginning with carbon, have been produced in dying or supernova stars by buildup from alpha particles (helium nuclei), contributing to an alternatingly larger abundance of elements with even atomic numbers (these are also more stable).
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The effect of odd-numbered chemical elements generally being more rare in the universe was empirically noticed in 1914, and is known as the Oddo–Harkins rule.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The following graph (log scale) shows abundance of elements in the Solar System.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Loose correlations have been observed between estimated elemental abundances in the universe and the nuclear binding energy curve (also called the *binding energy per nucleon*).
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Roughly speaking, the relative stability of various atomic nuclides in withstanding the extremely energetic conditions of Big Bang nucleosynthesis (BBN) has exerted a strong influence on the relative abundance of elements formed in the Big Bang, and during the development of the universe thereafter.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] See the article about nucleosynthesis for an explanation of how certain nuclear fusion processes in stars (such as carbon burning, etc.) create the elements heavier than hydrogen and helium.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] A similar alternation between even and odd atomic numbers can be observed in the nuclear binding energy curve in the neighborhood of carbon and oxygen, but here the loose correlation between relative abundance and binding energy ends.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The binding energy for beryllium (an even atomic number), for example, is *less* than the binding energy for boron (an odd atomic number), as illustrated in the nuclear binding energy curve.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Additionally, the alternation in the nuclear binding energy between even and odd atomic numbers resolves above oxygen as the graph increases steadily up to its peak at iron.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The semi-empirical mass formula (SEMF), also called *Weizsäcker's formula* or the *Bethe-Weizsäcker mass formula*, gives a theoretical explanation of the overall shape of the curve of nuclear binding energy.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Modern astronomy relies on understanding the abundance of elements in the Sun as part of cosmological models.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Abundance values are difficult to obtain: even photospheric or observational abundances depend upon models of solar atmospherics and radiation coupling.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] These astronomical abundance values are reported as logarithms of the ratio with hydrogen.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Hydrogen is set to an abundance of 12 on this scale.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The Sun's photosphere consists mostly of hydrogen and helium; the helium abundance varies between about 10.3 and 10.5 depending on the phase of the solar cycle; carbon is 8.47, neon is 8.29, oxygen is 7.69 and iron is estimated at 7.62.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The Earth formed from the same cloud of matter that formed the Sun, but the planets acquired different compositions during the formation and evolution of the Solar System.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] In turn, the history of Earth led to parts of the planet having differing concentrations of the elements.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The mass of the Earth is approximately 5.97×1024 kg.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] By mass, it is composed mostly of iron (32.1%), oxygen (30.1%), silicon (15.1%), magnesium (13.9%), sulfur (2.9%), nickel (1.8%), calcium (1.5%), and aluminium (1.4%); with the remaining 1.2% consisting of trace amounts of other elements.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The amount of oxygen, silicon, sulfur, carbon, and hydrogen in the Earth's core can only be inferred from theoretical models and consequently the abundance of these elements in the total Earth is not known precisely.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The remaining elemental composition is roughly typical of the "rocky" inner planets, which formed "inside" the "frost line" close to the Sun, where the young Sun's heat and stellar wind drove off volatile compounds into space.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The Earth retains oxygen as the second-largest component of its mass (and largest atomic fraction), mainly due to oxygen's high reactivity; this caused it to bond into silicate minerals which have a high melting point and low vapor pressure.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The mass-abundance of the nine most abundant elements in the Earth's crust is roughly: oxygen 46%, silicon 28%, aluminium 8.3%, iron 5.6%, calcium 4.2%, sodium 2.5%, magnesium 2.4%, potassium 2.0%, and titanium 0.61%.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Other elements occur at less than 0.15%.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] For a full list, see abundance of elements in Earth's crust.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The graph at right illustrates the relative atomic-abundance of the chemical elements in Earth's upper continental crust—the part that is relatively accessible for measurements and estimation.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] 5. the nine rarest "metals" – the six platinum group elements plus Au, Re, and Te (a metalloid) – in the yellow field.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] These are rare in the crust from being soluble in iron and thus concentrated in Earth's core.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Tellurium is the single most depleted element in the silicate Earth relative to cosmic abundance, because in addition to being concentrated as dense chalcogenides in the core it was severely depleted by preaccretional sorting in the nebula as volatile hydrogen telluride.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] There are two breaks where the unstable elements technetium (atomic number 43) and promethium (number 61) would be.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] These elements are surrounded by stable elements, yet their most stable isotopes have relatively short half-lives (~4 million years and ~18 years respectively).
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] These are thus extremely rare, since any primordial amounts of these elements have long since decayed.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] These two elements are now only produced naturally through spontaneous fission of very heavy radioactive elements (such as uranium, thorium, or the trace amounts of plutonium that exist in uranium ores), or by the interaction of certain other elements with cosmic rays.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Both technetium and promethium have been identified spectroscopically in the atmospheres of stars, where they are produced by ongoing nucleosynthetic processes.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] There are also breaks in the abundance graph where the six noble gases would be, since they are not chemically bound in the Earth's crust, and so their crustal abundance is not well-defined.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Oxygen and silicon are the most common elements in the crust.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] On Earth and rocky planets in general, silicon and oxygen are far more common than their cosmic abundance.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The reason is that they combine with each other to form silicate minerals.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Other cosmically common elements such as hydrogen, carbon and nitrogen form volatile compounds such as ammonia and methane that easily boil away into space from the heat of planetary formation and/or the Sun's light.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] "Rare" earth elements is a historical misnomer.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The persistence of the term reflects unfamiliarity rather than true rarity.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The more abundant rare earth elements are similarly concentrated in the crust compared to commonplace industrial metals such as chromium, nickel, copper, zinc, molybdenum, tin, tungsten, or lead.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The two least abundant stable rare earth elements (thulium and lutetium) are nearly 200 times more common than gold.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] However, in contrast to the ordinary base and precious metals, rare earth elements have very little tendency to become concentrated in exploitable ore deposits.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Consequently, most of the world's supply of rare earth elements comes from only a handful of sources.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Furthermore, the rare earth metals are all quite chemically similar to each other, and they are thus quite difficult to separate into quantities of the pure elements.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Differences in abundances of individual rare earth elements in the upper continental crust of the Earth represent the superposition of two effects, one nuclear and one geochemical.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] First, the rare earth elements with even atomic numbers (58Ce, 60Nd, ...) have greater cosmic and terrestrial abundances than the adjacent rare earth elements with odd atomic numbers (57La, 59Pr, ...).
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Second, the lighter rare earth elements are more incompatible (because they have larger ionic radii) and therefore more strongly concentrated in the continental crust than the heavier rare earth elements.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] In most rare earth ore deposits, the first four rare earth elements – lanthanum, cerium, praseodymium, and neodymium – constitute 80% to 99% of the total amount of rare earth metal that can be found in the ore.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The mass-abundance of the seven most abundant elements in the Earth's mantle is approximately: oxygen 44.3%, magnesium 22.3%, silicon 21.3%, iron 6.32%, calcium 2.48%, aluminium 2.29%, nickel 0.19%.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Due to mass segregation, the core of the Earth is believed to be primarily composed of iron (88.8%), with smaller amounts of nickel (5.8%), sulfur (4.5%), and less than 1% trace elements.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Sulfur, phosphorus, and all other elements are present in significantly lower proportions.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] According to the abundance curve graph, argon, a significant if not major component of the atmosphere, does not appear in the crust at all.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] This is because the atmosphere has a far smaller mass than the crust, so argon remaining in the crust contributes little to mass fraction there, while at the same time buildup of argon in the atmosphere has become large enough to be significant.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] By mass, human cells consist of 65–90% water (H2O), and a significant portion of the remainder is composed of carbon-containing organic molecules.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Oxygen therefore contributes a majority of a human body's mass, followed by carbon.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Almost 99% of the mass of the human body is made up of six elements: hydrogen (H), carbon (C), nitrogen (N), oxygen (O), calcium (Ca), and phosphorus (P).
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The next 0.75% is made up of the next five elements: potassium (K), sulfur (S), chlorine (Cl), sodium (Na), and magnesium (Mg).
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Only 17 elements are known for certain to be necessary to human life, with one additional element (fluorine) thought to be helpful for tooth enamel strength.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] A few more trace elements may play some role in the health of mammals.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Boron and silicon are notably necessary for plants but have uncertain roles in animals.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The elements aluminium and silicon, although very common in the earth's crust, are conspicuously rare in the human body.
[src:astrobiology/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Below is a periodic table highlighting nutritional elements.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) has listed acetaldehyde as a Group 1 carcinogen.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxins with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] In 1835, Liebig named it "aldehyde", and in the middle of the century the name was altered to "acetaldehyde".
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] In 2013, global production was about 438,000 tonnes.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Before 1962, ethanol and acetylene were the major sources of acetaldehyde.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Since then, ethylene is the dominant feedstock.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] In the 1970s, the world capacity of the Wacker-Hoechst direct oxidation process exceeded two million tonnes annually.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Smaller quantities can be prepared by the partial oxidation of ethanol in an exothermic reaction.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] This process typically is conducted over a silver catalyst at about 500–650 °C (950–1,200 °F).
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] This method is one of the oldest routes for the industrial preparation of acetaldehyde.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Prior to the Wacker process and the availability of cheap ethylene, acetaldehyde was produced by the hydration of acetylene.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The mechanism involves the intermediacy of vinyl alcohol, which tautomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The reaction is conducted at 90–95 °C (194–203 °F), and the acetaldehyde formed is separated from water and mercury and cooled to 25–30 °C (77–86 °F).
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] In the wet oxidation process, iron(III) sulfate is used to reoxidize the mercury back to the mercury(II) salt.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The resulting iron(II) sulfate is oxidized in a separate reactor with nitric acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The enzyme Acetylene hydratase discovered in the strictly anaerobic bacterium *Pelobacter acetylenicus* can catalyze an analogous reaction without involving any compounds of mercury.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] However, it has thus far not been brought to any large-scale or commercial use.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] In this endothermic process, ethanol vapor is passed at 260–290 °C over a copper-based catalyst.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The process was once attractive because of the value of the hydrogen coproduct, but in modern times is not economically viable.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The hydroformylation of methanol with catalysts like cobalt, nickel, or iron salts also produces acetaldehyde, although this process is of no industrial importance.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Similarly noncompetitive, acetaldehyde arises from synthesis gas with modest selectivity.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The equilibrium constant is 6×10−7 at room temperature, thus that the relative amount of the enol form in a sample of acetaldehyde is very small.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] At room temperature, acetaldehyde (CH3CH=O) is more stable than vinyl alcohol (CH2=CHOH) by 42.7 kJ/mol: Overall the keto-enol tautomerization occurs slowly but is catalyzed by acids.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Photo-induced keto-enol tautomerization is viable under atmospheric or stratospheric conditions.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] This photo-tautomerization is relevant to the Earth's atmosphere, because vinyl alcohol is thought to be a precursor to carboxylic acids in the atmosphere.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a common electrophile in organic synthesis.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] In addition reactions acetaldehyde is prochiral.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] It is used primarily as a source of the "CH3C+H(OH)" synthon in aldol reactions and related condensation reactions.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Grignard reagents and organolithium compounds react with MeCHO to give hydroxyethyl derivatives.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] In one of the more spectacular addition reactions, formaldehyde in the presence of calcium hydroxide adds to MeCHO to give pentaerythritol, C(CH2OH)4 and formate.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] In a Strecker reaction, acetaldehyde condenses with cyanide and ammonia to give, after hydrolysis, the amino acid alanine.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can condense with amines to yield imines; for example, with cyclohexylamine to give *N*-ethylidenecyclohexylamine.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] These imines can be used to direct subsequent reactions like an aldol condensation.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] It is also a building block in the synthesis of heterocyclic compounds.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] In one example, it converts, upon treatment with ammonia, to 5-ethyl-2-methylpyridine ("aldehyde-collidine").
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Three molecules of acetaldehyde condense to form "paraldehyde", a cyclic trimer containing C-O single bonds.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Similarly condensation of four molecules of acetaldehyde give the cyclic molecule metaldehyde.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Paraldehyde can be produced in good yields, using a sulfuric acid catalyst.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Metaldehyde is only obtained in a few percent yield and with cooling, often using HBr rather than H2SO4 as the catalyst.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] At −40 °C (−40 °F) in the presence of acid catalysts, polyacetaldehyde is produced.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] There are two stereomers of paraldehyde and four of metaldehyde.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The German chemist Valentin Hermann Weidenbusch (1821–1893) synthesized paraldehyde in 1848 by treating acetaldehyde with acid (either sulfuric or nitric acid) and cooling to 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] He found it quite remarkable that when paraldehyde was *heated* with a trace of the same acid, the reaction went the other way, recreating acetaldehyde.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Although vinyl alcohol is a tautomeric form of acetaldehyde (§ Tautomerization to vinyl alcohol), polyvinyl alcohol cannot be produced from acetaldehyde.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde forms a stable acetal upon reaction with ethanol under conditions that favor dehydration.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The product, CH3CH(OCH2CH3)2, is formally named 1,1-diethoxyethane but is commonly referred to as "acetal".
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] This can cause confusion as "acetal" is more commonly used to describe compounds with the functional groups RCH(OR')2 or RR'C(OR'')2 rather than referring to this specific compound — in fact, 1,1-diethoxyethane is also described as the diethyl acetal of acetaldehyde.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a precursor to vinylphosphonic acid, which is used to make adhesives and ion conductive membranes.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] In the liver, the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase oxidizes ethanol into acetaldehyde, which is then further oxidized into harmless acetic acid by acetaldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] These two oxidation reactions are coupled with the reduction of NAD+ to NADH.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] In the brain, the enzyme catalase is primarily responsible for oxidizing ethanol to acetaldehyde, and alcohol dehydrogenase plays a minor role.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The last steps of alcoholic fermentation in bacteria, plants, and yeast involve the conversion of pyruvate into acetaldehyde and carbon dioxide by the enzyme pyruvate decarboxylase, followed by the conversion of acetaldehyde into ethanol.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The latter reaction is again catalyzed by an alcohol dehydrogenase, now operating in the opposite direction.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Many East Asian people have an ALDH2 mutation which makes them significantly less efficient at oxidizing acetaldehyde.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] On consuming alcohol, their bodies tend to accumulate excessive amounts of acetaldehyde, causing the so-called alcohol flush reaction.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] They develop a characteristic flush on the face and body, along with "nausea, headache and general physical discomfort".
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Ingestion of the drug disulfiram, which inhibits ALDH2, leads to a similar reaction .
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Traditionally, acetaldehyde was mainly used as a precursor to acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] This application has declined because acetic acid is produced more efficiently from methanol by the Monsanto and Cativa processes.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an important precursor to pyridine derivatives, pentaerythritol, and crotonaldehyde.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Urea and acetaldehyde combine to give a useful resin.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Acetic anhydride reacts with acetaldehyde to give ethylidene diacetate, a precursor to vinyl acetate, which is used to produce polyvinyl acetate.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The global market for acetaldehyde is declining.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Demand has been impacted by changes in the production of plasticizer alcohols, which has shifted because *n*-butyraldehyde is less often produced from acetaldehyde, instead being generated by hydroformylation of propylene.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Likewise, acetic acid, once produced from acetaldehyde, is made predominantly by the lower-cost methanol carbonylation process.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The impact on demand has led to increase in prices and thus slowdown in the market.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] China is the largest consumer of acetaldehyde in the world, accounting for almost half of global consumption in 2012.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Major use has been the production of acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Other uses such as pyridines and pentaerythritol are expected to grow faster than acetic acid, but the volumes are not large enough to offset the decline in acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] As a consequence, overall acetaldehyde consumption in China may grow slightly at 1.6% per year through 2018.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Western Europe is the second-largest consumer of acetaldehyde worldwide, accounting for 20% of world consumption in 2012.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] As with China, the Western European acetaldehyde market is expected to increase only very slightly at 1% per year during 2012–2018.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] However, Japan could emerge as a potential consumer for acetaldehyde in the next five years due to newfound use in commercial production of butadiene.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The supply of butadiene has been volatile in Japan and the rest of Asia.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] This should provide the much needed boost to the flat market, as of 2013.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The threshold limit value is 25 ppm (STEL/ceiling value) and the MAK (Maximum Workplace Concentration) is 50 ppm.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] At 50 ppm acetaldehyde, no irritation or local tissue damage in the nasal mucosa is observed.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] When taken up by the organism, acetaldehyde is metabolized rapidly in the liver to acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Only a small proportion is exhaled unchanged.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] After intravenous injection, the half-life in the blood is approximately 90 seconds.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Many serious cases of acute intoxication have been recorded.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde naturally breaks down in the human body.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an irritant of the skin, eyes, mucous membranes, throat, and respiratory tract.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] This occurs at concentrations as low as 1000 ppm.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Symptoms of exposure to this compound include nausea, vomiting, and headache.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] These symptoms may not happen immediately.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The perception threshold for acetaldehyde in air is in the range between 0.07 and 0.25 ppm.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] At such concentrations, the fruity odor of acetaldehyde is apparent.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Conjunctival irritations have been observed after a 15-minute exposure to concentrations of 25 and 50 ppm, but transient conjunctivitis and irritation of the respiratory tract have been reported after exposure to 200 ppm acetaldehyde for 15 minutes.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] In addition, acetaldehyde is damaging to DNA and causes abnormal muscle development as it binds to proteins.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde induces DNA interstrand crosslinks, a form of DNA damage.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] These can be repaired by either of two replication-coupled DNA repair pathways.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The first is referred to as the FA pathway, because it employs gene products defective in Fanconi's anemia patients.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] This repair pathway results in increased mutation frequency and altered mutational spectrum.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The second repair pathway requires replication fork convergence, breakage of the acetaldehyde crosslink, translesion synthesis by a Y-family DNA polymerase and homologous recombination.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] People with a genetic deficiency for the enzyme responsible for the conversion of acetaldehyde into acetic acid may have a greater risk of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] A study of 818 heavy drinkers found that those exposed to more acetaldehyde than normal through a genetic variant of the gene encoding for ADH1C, ADH1C*1, are at greater risk of developing cancers of the upper gastrointestinal tract and liver.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The drug disulfiram (Antabuse) inhibits acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, an enzyme that oxidizes the compound into acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Metabolism of ethanol forms acetaldehyde before acetaldehyde dehydrogenase forms acetic acid, but with the enzyme inhibited, acetaldehyde accumulates.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] If one consumes ethanol while taking disulfiram, the hangover effect of ethanol is felt more rapidly and intensely (disulfiram-alcohol reaction).
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] As such, disulfiram is sometimes used as a deterrent for alcoholics wishing to stay sober.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a potential contaminant in workplace, indoors, and ambient environments.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Moreover, the majority of humans spend more than 90% of their time in indoor environments, increasing any exposure and the risk to human health.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] In a study in France, the mean indoor concentration of acetaldehydes measured in 16 homes was approximately seven times higher than the outside acetaldehyde concentration.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The living room had a mean of 18.1±17.5 μg m−3 and the bedroom was 18.2±16.9 μg m−3, whereas the outdoor air had a mean concentration of 2.3±2.6 μg m−3.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] It has been concluded that volatile organic compounds (VOC) such as benzene, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, toluene, and xylenes have to be considered priority pollutants with respect to their health effects.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] It has been pointed that in renovated or completely new buildings, the VOCs concentration levels are often several orders of magnitude higher.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The main sources of acetaldehydes in homes include building materials, laminate, PVC flooring, varnished wood flooring, and varnished cork/pine flooring (found in the varnish, not the wood).
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] It is also found in plastics, oil-based and water-based paints, in composite wood ceilings, particle-board, plywood, treated pine wood, and laminated chipboard furniture.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The use of acetaldehyde is widespread in different industries, and it may be released into waste water or the air during production, use, transportation and storage.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Sources of acetaldehyde include fuel combustion emissions from stationary internal combustion engines and power plants that burn fossil fuels, wood, or trash, oil and gas extraction, refineries, cement kilns, lumber and wood mills and paper mills.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also present in automobile and diesel exhaust.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] As a result, acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxics with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Natural tobacco polysaccharides, including cellulose, have been shown to be the primary precursors making acetaldehyde a significant constituent of tobacco smoke.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] It has been demonstrated to have a synergistic effect with nicotine in rodent studies of addiction.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also the most abundant carcinogen in tobacco smoke; it is dissolved into the saliva while smoking.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde has been found in cannabis smoke.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] This finding emerged through the use of new chemical techniques that demonstrated the acetaldehyde present was causing DNA damage in laboratory settings.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Many microbes produce acetaldehyde from ethanol, but they have a lower capacity to eliminate the acetaldehyde, which can lead to the accumulation of acetaldehyde in saliva, stomach acid, and intestinal contents.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Fermented food and many alcoholic beverages can also contain significant amounts of acetaldehyde.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde, derived from mucosal or microbial oxidation of ethanol, tobacco smoke, and diet, appears to act as a cumulative carcinogen in the upper digestive tract of humans.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] According to European Commission's Scientific Committee on Consumer Safety's (SCCS) "Opinion on Acetaldehyde" (2012) the cosmetic products special risk limit is 5 mg/L and acetaldehyde should not be used in mouth-washing products.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can be produced by the photo-oxidation of polyethylene terephthalate (PET), via a Type II Norrish reaction.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] Although the levels produced by this process are minute acetaldehyde has an exceedingly low taste/odor threshold of around 20–40 ppb and can cause an off-taste in bottled water.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The level at which an average consumer could detect acetaldehyde is still considerably lower than any toxicity.
[src:astrobiology/acetaldehyde] The yeast *Candida albicans* in patients with potentially carcinogenic oral diseases has been shown to produce acetaldehyde in quantities sufficient to cause problems.
[src:astrobiology/acetamide] Alternatively acetamide can be obtained in excellent yield via ammonolysis of acetylacetone under conditions commonly used in reductive amination.
[src:astrobiology/acetamide] It can also be made from anhydrous acetic acid, acetonitrile and very well dried hydrogen chloride gas, using an ice bath, alongside more valuable reagent acetyl chloride.
[src:astrobiology/acetamide] Yield is typically low (up to 35%), and the acetamide made this way is generated as a salt with HCl.
[src:astrobiology/acetamide] Acetamide is used as a plasticizer and an industrial solvent.
[src:astrobiology/acetamide] Molten acetamide is good solvent with a broad range of applicability.
[src:astrobiology/acetamide] Notably, its dielectric constant is higher than most organic solvents, allowing it to dissolve inorganic compounds with solubilities closely analogous to that of water.
[src:astrobiology/acetamide] Acetamide has uses in electrochemistry and the organic synthesis of pharmaceuticals, pesticides, and antioxidants for plastics.
[src:astrobiology/acetamide] Acetamide has been detected near the center of the Milky Way galaxy.
[src:astrobiology/acetamide] This finding is potentially significant because acetamide has an amide bond, similar to the essential bond between amino acids in proteins.
[src:astrobiology/acetamide] This finding lends support to the theory that organic molecules that can lead to life (as we know it on Earth) can form in space.
[src:astrobiology/acetamide] In addition, acetamide is found infrequently on burning coal dumps, as a mineral of the same name.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is the second simplest carboxylic acid (after formic acid).
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] It is an important chemical reagent and industrial chemical across various fields, used primarily in the production of cellulose acetate for photographic film, polyvinyl acetate for wood glue, and synthetic fibres and fabrics.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] In households, diluted acetic acid is often used in descaling agents.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] In the food industry, acetic acid is controlled by the food additive code E260 as an acidity regulator and as a condiment.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] In biochemistry, the acetyl group, derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] When bound to coenzyme A, it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The global demand for acetic acid as of 2023 is about 17.88 million metric tonnes per year (t/a).
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Most of the world's acetic acid is produced via the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Its production and subsequent industrial use poses health hazards to workers, including incidental skin damage and chronic respiratory injuries from inhalation.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The trivial name "acetic acid" is the most commonly used and preferred IUPAC name.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The systematic name "ethanoic acid", a valid IUPAC name, is constructed according to the substitutive nomenclature.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The name "acetic acid" derives from the Latin word for vinegar, "*acetum*", which means "to sour" in relation to the bitter taste of fermented fruits.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] "Glacial acetic acid" is a name for water-free (anhydrous) acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Similar to the German name "Eisessig" ("ice vinegar"), the name comes from the solid ice-like crystals that form with agitation, slightly below room temperature at 16.6 °C (61.9 °F).
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can never be truly water-free in an atmosphere that contains water, so the presence of 0.1% water in glacial acetic acid lowers its melting point by 0.2 °C.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] A common symbol for acetic acid is AcOH (or HOAc), where Ac is the pseudoelement symbol representing the acetyl group CH3−C(=O)−; the conjugate base, acetate (CH3COO−), is thus represented as AcO−.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetate is the ion resulting from loss of H+ from acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The name "acetate" can also refer to a salt containing this anion, or an ester of acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] (The symbol Ac for the acetyl functional group is not to be confused with the symbol Ac for the element actinium; context prevents confusion among organic chemists).
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] To better reflect its structure, acetic acid is often written as CH3−C(O)OH, CH3−C(=O)−OH, CH3COOH, and CH3CO2H.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] In the context of acid–base reactions, the abbreviation HAc is sometimes used, where Ac in this case is a symbol for acetate (rather than acetyl).
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The carboxymethyl functional group derived from removing one hydrogen from the methyl group of acetic acid has the chemical formula −CH2−C(=O)−OH.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetic acid, the dilute solution of which is known as vinegar, is likely the first acid to be produced in large quantities in history.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Vinegar has been used for at least 10,000 years as it is the natural result of exposure of beer and wine to air because acetic acid-producing bacteria are present globally.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Hippocrates used vinegar as an antiseptic and as a remedy for numerous conditions including fever, constipation, ulcers, and pleurisy.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Ancient Romans boiled soured wine to produce a highly sweet syrup called *sapa*.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Sapa that was produced in lead pots was rich in lead acetate, a sweet substance also called *sugar of lead* or *sugar of Saturn*, which contributed to lead poisoning among the Roman aristocracy.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] In the 16th-century German alchemist Andreas Libavius described the production of acetone from the dry distillation of lead acetate, ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The presence of water in vinegar has such a profound effect on acetic acid's properties that for centuries chemists believed that glacial acetic acid and the acid found in vinegar were two different substances.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] French chemist Pierre Adet proved them identical.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] In 1845 German chemist Hermann Kolbe synthesized acetic acid from inorganic compounds for the first time.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] This reaction sequence consisted of chlorination of carbon disulfide to carbon tetrachloride, followed by pyrolysis to tetrachloroethylene and aqueous chlorination to trichloroacetic acid, and concluded with electrolytic reduction to acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] By 1910, most glacial acetic acid was obtained from pyroligneous liquor, a product of the destructive distillation of wood.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The acetic acid was isolated by treatment with milk of lime, and the resulting calcium acetate was then acidified with sulfuric acid to recover acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] At that time, Germany was producing 10,000 tons of glacial acetic acid, around 30% of which was used for the manufacture of indigo dye.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Because both methanol and carbon monoxide are commodity raw materials, methanol carbonylation long appeared to be an attractive method of acetic acid production.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Henri Dreyfus at British Celanese developed a methanol carbonylation pilot plant as early as 1925.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] However, a lack of practical materials that could contain the corrosive reaction mixture at the high pressures needed (200 atm or more) discouraged commercialization of these routes.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The first commercial methanol carbonylation process, which used a cobalt catalyst, was developed by German chemical company BASF in 1963.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] In 1968, a rhodium-based catalyst (*cis*−[Rh(CO)2I2]−) was discovered that could operate efficiently at lower pressure with almost no by-products.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] US chemical company Monsanto Company built the first plant using this catalyst in 1970, and rhodium-catalyzed methanol carbonylation became the dominant method of acetic acid production (see Monsanto process).
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] In the late 1990s, BP Chemicals commercialized the Cativa catalyst ([Ir(CO)2I2]−), which is promoted by iridium for greater efficiency.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Known as the Cativa process, the iridium-catalyzed production of glacial acetic acid is greener, and has largely supplanted the Monsanto process, often in the same production plants.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Interstellar acetic acid was first detected in the Sagittarius B2 North molecular cloud (also known as the Sgr B2 Large Molecule Heimat source).
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Because of this release of the proton (H+), acetic acid has acidic character.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] In aqueous solution, it has a pKa value of 4.76.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Its conjugate base is acetate (CH3COO−).
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] A 1.0 M solution (about the concentration of domestic vinegar) has a pH of 2.4, indicating that merely 0.4% of the acetic acid molecules are ionized.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] In solid acetic acid, the molecules form chains of individual molecules interconnected by hydrogen bonds.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] In the vapour phase at 120 °C (248 °F), dimers can be detected.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Dimers also occur in the liquid phase in dilute solutions with non-hydrogen-bonding solvents, and to a certain extent in pure acetic acid, but are disrupted by hydrogen-bonding solvents.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The dissociation enthalpy of the dimer is estimated at 65.0–66.0 kJ/mol, and the dissociation entropy at 154–157 J mol−1 K−1.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Other carboxylic acids engage in similar intermolecular hydrogen bonding interactions.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Liquid acetic acid is a hydrophilic (polar) protic solvent, similar to ethanol and water.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] With a relative static permittivity (dielectric constant) of 6.2, it dissolves not only polar compounds such as inorganic salts and sugars, but also non-polar compounds such as oils as well as polar solutes.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] It is miscible with polar and non-polar solvents such as water, chloroform, and hexane.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] With higher alkanes (starting with octane), acetic acid is not miscible at all compositions, and solubility of acetic acid in alkanes declines with longer n-alkanes.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The solvent and miscibility properties of acetic acid make it a useful industrial chemical, for example, as a solvent in the production of dimethyl terephthalate.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] At physiological pHs, acetic acid is usually fully ionized to acetate in aqueous solution.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The acetyl group, formally derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Typically, it is bound to coenzyme A by acetyl-CoA synthetase enzymes, where it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Unlike longer-chain carboxylic acids (the fatty acids), acetic acid does not occur in natural triglycerides.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Most of the acetate generated in cells for use in acetyl-CoA is synthesized directly from ethanol or pyruvate.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] However, the artificial triglyceride triacetin (glycerine triacetate) is a common food additive and is found in cosmetics and topical medicines; this additive is metabolized to glycerol and acetic acid in the body.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced and excreted by acetic acid bacteria, notably the genus *Acetobacter* and *Clostridium acetobutylicum*.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] These bacteria are found universally in foodstuffs, water, and soil, and acetic acid is produced naturally as fruits and other foods spoil.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is also a component of the vaginal lubrication of humans and other primates, where it appears to serve as a mild antibacterial agent.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced industrially both naturally via bacterial fermentation and synthetically.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] About 75% of acetic acid made for use in the chemical industry is made by the carbonylation of methanol, explained below.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The biological route accounts for only about 10% of world production, but it remains important for the production of vinegar because many food purity laws require vinegar used in foods to be of biological origin.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Other processes are methyl formate isomerization, conversion of syngas to acetic acid, and gas phase oxidation of ethylene and ethanol.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can be purified via fractional freezing using an ice bath.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The water and other impurities will remain liquid while the acetic acid will precipitate out.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] As of 2003–2005, total worldwide production of virgin acetic acid was estimated at 5 Mt/a (million tonnes per year), approximately half of which was produced in the United States.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] European production was approximately 1 Mt/a and declining, while Japanese production was 0.7 Mt/a.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Another 1.5 Mt were recycled each year, bringing the total world market to 6.5 Mt/a.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Since then, the global production has increased from 10.7 Mt/a in 2010 to 17.88 Mt/a in 2023.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The two biggest producers of virgin acetic acid are Celanese and BP Chemicals.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Other major producers include Millennium Chemicals, Sterling Chemicals, Samsung, Eastman, and Svensk Etanolkemi.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Most acetic acid is produced by methanol carbonylation.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The process involves iodomethane as an intermediate, and occurs in three steps.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] A metal carbonyl catalyst is needed for the carbonylation (step 2).
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Two related processes exist for the carbonylation of methanol: the rhodium-catalyzed Monsanto process, and the iridium-catalyzed Cativa process.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The latter process is greener and more efficient and has largely supplanted the former process.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Catalytic amounts of water are used in both processes, but the Cativa process requires less, so the water-gas shift reaction is suppressed, and fewer by-products are formed.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] By altering the process conditions, acetic anhydride may also be produced in plants using rhodium catalysis.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Prior to the commercialization of the Monsanto process, most acetic acid was produced by oxidation of acetaldehyde.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] This remains the second-most-important manufacturing method, although it is usually not competitive with the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The acetaldehyde can be produced by hydration of acetylene.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] This was the dominant technology in the early 1900s.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Such oxidations require metal catalyst, such as the naphthenate salts of manganese, cobalt, and chromium.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The typical reaction is conducted at temperatures and pressures designed to be as hot as possible while still keeping the butane a liquid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Typical reaction conditions are 150 °C (302 °F) and 55 atm.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Side-products may also form, including butanone, ethyl acetate, formic acid, and propionic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] These side-products are also commercially valuable, and the reaction conditions may be altered to produce more of them where needed.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] However, the separation of acetic acid from these by-products adds to the cost of the process.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Similar conditions and catalysts are used for butane oxidation, the oxygen in air to produce acetic acid can oxidize acetaldehyde.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Using modern catalysts, this reaction can have an acetic acid yield greater than 95%.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The major side-products are ethyl acetate, formic acid, and formaldehyde, all of which have lower boiling points than acetic acid and are readily separated by distillation.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetaldehyde may be prepared from ethylene via the Wacker process, and then oxidized as above.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] In more recent times, chemical company Showa Denko, which opened an ethylene oxidation plant in Ōita, Japan, in 1997, commercialized a cheaper single-stage conversion of ethylene to acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The process is catalyzed by a palladium metal catalyst supported on a heteropoly acid such as silicotungstic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] It is thought to be competitive with methanol carbonylation for smaller plants (100–250 kt/a), depending on the local price of ethylene.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] For most of human history, acetic acid bacteria of the genus *Acetobacter* have made acetic acid, in the form of vinegar.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Given sufficient oxygen, these bacteria can produce vinegar from a variety of alcoholic foodstuffs.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Commonly used feeds include apple cider, wine, and fermented grain, malt, rice, or potato mashes.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] A dilute alcohol solution inoculated with *Acetobacter* and kept in a warm, airy place will become vinegar over the course of a few months.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Industrial vinegar-making methods accelerate this process by improving the supply of oxygen to the bacteria.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The first batches of vinegar produced by fermentation probably followed errors in the winemaking process.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] If must is fermented at too high a temperature, acetobacter will overwhelm the yeast naturally occurring on the grapes.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] As the demand for vinegar for culinary, medical, and sanitary purposes increased, vintners quickly learned to use other organic materials to produce vinegar in the hot summer months before the grapes were ripe and ready for processing into wine.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] This method was slow, however, and not always successful, as the vintners did not understand the process.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] One of the first modern commercial processes was the "fast method" or "German method", first practised in Germany in 1823.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] In this process, fermentation takes place in a tower packed with wood shavings or charcoal.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The alcohol-containing feed is trickled into the top of the tower, and fresh air supplied from the bottom by either natural or forced convection.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The improved air supply in this process cut the time to prepare vinegar from months to weeks.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Nowadays, most vinegar is made in submerged tank culture, first described in 1949 by Otto Hromatka and Heinrich Ebner.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] In this method, alcohol is fermented to vinegar in a continuously stirred tank, and oxygen is supplied by bubbling air through the solution.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Using modern applications of this method, vinegar of 15% acetic acid can be prepared in only 24 hours in batch process, even 20% in 60-hour fed-batch process.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Species of anaerobic bacteria, including members of the genus *Clostridium* or *Acetobacterium*, can convert sugars to acetic acid directly without creating ethanol as an intermediate.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] This ability of *Clostridium* to metabolize sugars directly, or to produce acetic acid from less costly inputs, suggests that these bacteria could produce acetic acid more efficiently than ethanol-oxidizers like *Acetobacter*.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] However, *Clostridium* bacteria are less acid-tolerant than *Acetobacter*.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Even the most acid-tolerant *Clostridium* strains can produce vinegar in concentrations of only a few percent, compared to *Acetobacter* strains that can produce vinegar in concentrations up to 20%.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] At present, it remains more cost-effective to produce vinegar using *Acetobacter*, rather than using *Clostridium* and concentrating it.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] As a result, although acetogenic bacteria have been known since 1940, their industrial use is confined to a few niche applications.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is a chemical reagent for the production of chemical compounds.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The largest single use of acetic acid is in the production of vinyl acetate monomer, closely followed by acetic anhydride and ester production.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The volume of acetic acid used in vinegar is comparatively small.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The primary use of acetic acid is the production of vinyl acetate monomer (VAM).
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] In 2008, this application was estimated to consume a third of the world's production of acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The reaction consists of ethylene and acetic acid with oxygen over a palladium catalyst, conducted in the gas phase.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Vinyl acetate can be polymerized to polyvinyl acetate or other polymers, which are components in paints and adhesives.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The major esters of acetic acid are commonly used as solvents for inks, paints and coatings.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The esters include ethyl acetate, *n*-butyl acetate, isobutyl acetate, and propyl acetate.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] For example, acetic acid and ethanol gives ethyl acetate and water.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Most acetate esters, however, are produced from acetaldehyde using the Tishchenko reaction.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] In addition, ether acetates are used as solvents for nitrocellulose, acrylic lacquers, varnish removers, and wood stains.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] First, glycol monoethers are produced from ethylene oxide or propylene oxide with alcohol, which are then esterified with acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The three major products are ethylene glycol monoethyl ether acetate (EEA), ethylene glycol monobutyl ether acetate (EBA), and propylene glycol monomethyl ether acetate (PMA, more commonly known as PGMEA in semiconductor manufacturing processes, where it is used as a resist solvent).
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] This application consumes about 15% to 20% of worldwide acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Ether acetates, for example EEA, have been shown to be harmful to human reproduction.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The product of the condensation of two molecules of acetic acid is acetic anhydride.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The worldwide production of acetic anhydride is a major application, and uses approximately 25% to 30% of the global production of acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The main process involves dehydration of acetic acid to give ketene at 700–750 °C.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is an acetylation agent.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] As such, its major application is for cellulose acetate, a synthetic textile also used for photographic film, which is produced by reacting cellulose with acetic acid and acetic anhydride in the presence of sulfuric acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is also a reagent for the production of heroin and other compounds.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] As a polar protic solvent, acetic acid is frequently used for recrystallization to purify organic compounds.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as a solvent in the production of terephthalic acid (TPA), the raw material for polyethylene terephthalate (PET).
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] In 2006, about 20% of acetic acid was used for TPA production.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is often used as a solvent for reactions involving carbocations, such as Friedel-Crafts alkylation.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] For example, one stage in the commercial manufacture of synthetic camphor involves a Wagner-Meerwein rearrangement of camphene to isobornyl acetate; here acetic acid acts both as a solvent and as a nucleophile to trap the rearranged carbocation.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is used in analytical chemistry for the estimation of weakly alkaline substances such as organic amides.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is a much weaker base than water, so the amide behaves as a strong base in this medium.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] It then can be titrated using a solution in glacial acetic acid of a very strong acid, such as perchloric acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetic acid injection into a tumor has been used to treat cancer since the 1800s.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as part of cervical cancer screening in many areas in the developing world.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The acid is applied to the cervix and if an area of white appears after about a minute the test is positive.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is an effective antiseptic when used as a 1% solution, with broad spectrum of activity against streptococci, staphylococci, pseudomonas, enterococci and others.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] It may be used to treat skin infections caused by pseudomonas strains resistant to typical antibiotics.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] While diluted acetic acid is used in iontophoresis, no high quality evidence supports this treatment for rotator cuff disease.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] As a treatment for otitis externa, it is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Vinegar is typically no less than 4% acetic acid by mass.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Legal limits on acetic acid content vary by jurisdiction.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Vinegar is used directly as a condiment, and in the pickling of vegetables and other foods.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Table vinegar tends to be more diluted (4% to 8% acetic acid), while commercial food pickling employs solutions that are more concentrated.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The proportion of acetic acid used worldwide as vinegar is not as large as industrial uses, but it is by far the oldest and best-known application.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetic acid undergoes the typical chemical reactions of a carboxylic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Upon treatment with a standard base, it converts to metal acetate and water.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] With strong bases (e.g., organolithium reagents), it can be doubly deprotonated to give LiCH2COOLi.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The OH group is the main site of reaction, as illustrated by the conversion of acetic acid to acetyl chloride.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Other substitution derivatives include acetic anhydride; this anhydride is produced by loss of water from two molecules of acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Esters of acetic acid can likewise be formed via Fischer esterification, and amides can be formed.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Because aluminium forms a passivating acid-resistant film of aluminium oxide, aluminium tanks are used to transport acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Containers lined with glass, stainless steel or polyethylene are also used for this purpose.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] A colour reaction for salts of acetic acid is iron(III) chloride solution, which results in a deeply red colour that disappears after acidification.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] A more sensitive test uses lanthanum nitrate with iodine and ammonia to give a blue solution.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Acetates when heated with arsenic trioxide form cacodyl oxide, which can be detected by its malodorous vapours.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Organic or inorganic salts are produced from acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Halogenated acetic acids are produced from acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Amounts of acetic acid used in these other applications together account for another 5–10% of acetic acid use worldwide.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Prolonged inhalation exposure (eight hours) to acetic acid vapours at 10 ppm can produce some irritation of eyes, nose, and throat; at 100 ppm marked lung irritation and possible damage to lungs, eyes, and skin may result.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Vapour concentrations of 1,000 ppm cause marked irritation of eyes, nose and upper respiratory tract and cannot be tolerated.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] These predictions were based on animal experiments and industrial exposure.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] In 12 workers exposed for two or more years to an airborne average concentration of 51 ppm acetic acid (estimated), symptoms of conjunctive irritation, upper respiratory tract irritation, and hyperkeratotic dermatitis were produced.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Exposure to 50 ppm or more is intolerable to most persons and results in intensive lacrimation and irritation of the eyes, nose, and throat, with pharyngeal oedema and chronic bronchitis.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Unacclimatized humans experience extreme eye and nasal irritation at concentrations in excess of 25 ppm, and conjunctivitis from concentrations below 10 ppm has been reported.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid (≥ 25%) is corrosive to skin.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] These burns or blisters may not appear until hours after exposure.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] The hazardous properties of acetic acid are dependent on the concentration of the (typically aqueous) solution, with the most significant increases in hazard levels at thresholds of 25% and 90% acetic acid concentration by weight.
[src:astrobiology/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid can be ignited only with difficulty at standard temperature and pressure, but becomes a flammable risk in temperatures greater than 39 °C (102 °F), and can form explosive mixtures with air at increased temperatures with explosive limits of 5.4–16% concentration.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone is miscible with water and serves as an important organic solvent in industry, home, and laboratory.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] About 6.7 million tonnes were produced worldwide in 2010, mainly for use as a solvent and for production of methyl methacrylate and bisphenol A, which are precursors to widely used plastics.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] It is a common building block in organic chemistry.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] It serves as a solvent in household products such as nail polish remover and paint thinner.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] It has volatile organic compound (VOC)-exempt status in the United States.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone is produced and disposed of in the human body through normal metabolic processes.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Small quantities of it are present naturally in blood and urine.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] People with diabetic ketoacidosis produce it in larger amounts.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Medical ketogenic diets that increase ketone bodies (acetone, β-hydroxybutyric acid and acetoacetic acid) in the blood are used to suppress epileptic attacks in children with treatment-resistant epilepsy.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] From the 17th century, and before modern developments in organic chemistry nomenclature, acetone was given many different names.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] They included "spirit of Saturn", which was given when it was thought to be a compound of lead and, later, "pyro-acetic spirit" and "pyro-acetic ester".
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Prior to the name "acetone" being coined by French chemists, it was named "mesit" (from the Greek μεσίτης, meaning mediator) by Carl Reichenbach, who also said that methyl alcohol consisted of mesit and ethyl alcohol.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Names derived from mesit include mesitylene and mesityl oxide which were first synthesised from acetone.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] In 1839, the name "acetone" began to be used, because it was obtained from acetic acid.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Unlike many compounds with the *acet-* prefix which have a 2-carbon chain, acetone has a 3-carbon chain.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] That has caused confusion because there can not be a ketone with 2 carbons.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] The prefix refers to acetone's relation to vinegar (*acetum* in Latin, also the source of the words "acid" and "acetic"), rather than its chemical structure.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone was first produced by Andreas Libavius in 1606 by distillation of lead(II) acetate.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] In 1832, French chemist Jean-Baptiste Dumas and German chemist Justus von Liebig determined the empirical formula for acetone.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] In 1833, French chemists Antoine Bussy and Michel Chevreul decided to name acetone by adding the suffix *-one* to the stem of the corresponding acid (viz, acetic acid) just as a similarly prepared product of what was then confused with margaric acid was named margarone.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] By 1852, Alexander William Williamson, an English chemist, realized that acetone was methyl acetyl; the following year, the French chemist Charles Frédéric Gerhardt concurred.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] In 1865, a German chemist, August Kekulé published the modern structural formula for acetone.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Johann Josef Loschmidt had presented the structure of acetone in 1861, but his privately published booklet received little attention.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] During World War I, Chaim Weizmann developed the biochemical process for industrial production of acetone (Weizmann Process).
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone is produced directly or indirectly from propene.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Approximately 83% of acetone is produced via the cumene process; as a result, acetone production is tied to phenol production.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Other processes involve the direct oxidation of propylene (Wacker-Hoechst process), or the hydration of propylene to give 2-propanol, which is oxidized (dehydrogenated) to acetone.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Previously, acetone was produced by the dry distillation of acetates, for example calcium acetate in ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] After that time during World War I, acetone was produced using acetone-butanol-ethanol fermentation with *Clostridium acetobutylicum* bacteria, which was developed by Chaim Weizmann (later the first president of Israel) in order to help the British war effort, in the preparation of Cordite.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] This acetone-butanol-ethanol fermentation was eventually abandoned when newer methods with better yields were found.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] In 2010, the worldwide production capacity for acetone was estimated at 6.7 million tonnes per year.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] With 1.56 million tonnes per year, the United States had the highest production capacity, followed by Taiwan and China.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] The largest producer of acetone is INEOS Phenol, owning 17% of the world's capacity, with also significant capacity (7–8%) by Mitsui, Sunoco and Shell in 2010.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] INEOS Phenol also owns the world's largest production site (420,000 tonnes/annum) in Beveren, Belgium.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] The spot price of acetone in summer 2011 was 1100–1250 USD/tonne in the United States.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Humans exhale several milligrams of acetone per day and it arises from the decarboxylation of acetoacetate.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Small amounts of acetone are produced in the body by the decarboxylation of ketone bodies.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Certain dietary patterns including prolonged fasting and high-fat low-carbohydrate dieting, can produce ketosis, in which acetone is formed in body tissue.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Certain health conditions, such as alcoholism and diabetes, can produce ketoacidosis, uncontrollable ketosis that leads to a sharp, and potentially fatal, increase in the acidity of the blood.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Since it is a byproduct of fermentation, acetone is a byproduct of the distillery industry.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] It is produced by terrestrial vegetation, undefined ocean processes, incomplete combustion of biomass, or oxidation of hydrocarbons in the atmosphere.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Like most ketones, acetone exhibits the keto–enol tautomerism in which the nominal keto structure (CH3)2C=O of acetone itself is in equilibrium with the enol isomer (CH3)C(OH)=(CH2) (**prop-1-en-2-ol**).
[src:astrobiology/acetone] In acetone vapor at ambient temperature, only 2.4×10−7% of the molecules are in the enol form.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] In the presence of suitable catalysts, two acetone molecules also combine to form the compound diacetone alcohol (CH3)C=O(CH2)C(OH)(CH3)2, which on dehydration gives mesityl oxide (CH3)C=O(CH)=C(CH3)2.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] This product can further combine with another acetone molecule, with loss of another molecule of water, yielding phorone and other compounds.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone is a weak Lewis base that forms adducts with soft acids like I2 and hard acids like phenol.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone also forms complexes with divalent metals.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Under ultraviolet light, acetone fluoresces.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] The flame temperature of pure acetone is 1980 °C.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] At its melting point (−96 °C) is claimed to polymerize to give a white elastic solid, soluble in acetone, stable for several hours at room temperature.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] To do so, a vapor of acetone is co-condensed with magnesium as a catalyst onto a very cold surface.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] The outcome of irradiation of acetone is wavelength dependent.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] The latter process is relevant to the atmospheric chemistry of acetone.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone can then be metabolized either by CYP2E1 via methylglyoxal to D-lactate and pyruvate, and ultimately glucose/energy, or by a different pathway via propylene glycol to pyruvate, lactate, acetate (usable for energy) and propionaldehyde.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] About a third of the world's acetone is used as a solvent, and a quarter is consumed as acetone cyanohydrin, a precursor to methyl methacrylate.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone is used to synthesize methyl methacrylate.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] The third major use of acetone (about 20%) is synthesizing bisphenol A.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Bisphenol A is a component of many polymers such as polycarbonates, polyurethanes, and epoxy resins.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Many millions of kilograms of acetone are consumed in the production of the solvents methyl isobutyl alcohol and methyl isobutyl ketone.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] These products arise via an initial aldol condensation to give diacetone alcohol.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Condensation with acetylene gives 2-methylbut-3-yn-2-ol, precursor to synthetic terpenes and terpenoids.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone is a good solvent for many plastics and some synthetic fibers.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] It is used for thinning polyester resin, cleaning tools used with it, and dissolving two-part epoxies and superglue before they harden.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] It is used as one of the volatile components of some paints and varnishes.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Although itself flammable, acetone is used extensively as a solvent for the safe transportation and storage of acetylene, which cannot be safely pressurized as a pure compound.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Vessels containing a porous material are first filled with acetone followed by acetylene, which dissolves into the acetone.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] One litre of acetone can dissolve around 250 litres of acetylene at a pressure of 10 bars (1.0 MPa).
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone is used as a solvent by the pharmaceutical industry and as a denaturant in denatured alcohol.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone is also present as an excipient in some pharmaceutical drugs.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] A variety of organic reactions employ acetone as a polar, aprotic solvent, e.g. the Jones oxidation.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Because acetone is cheap, volatile, and dissolves or decomposes with most laboratory chemicals, an acetone rinse is the standard technique to remove solid residues from laboratory glassware before a final wash.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Despite common desiccatory use, acetone dries only via bulk displacement and dilution.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] It forms no azeotropes with water (see azeotrope tables).
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone also removes certain stains from microscope slides.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] An acetone/dry ice mixture cools many low-temperature reactions.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Make-up artists use acetone to remove skin adhesive from the netting of wigs and mustaches by immersing the item in an acetone bath, then removing the softened glue residue with a stiff brush.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone is a main ingredient in many nail polish removers because it breaks down nail polish.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] It is used for all types of nail polish removal, like gel nail polish, dip powder and acrylic nails.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] The chemical modifies peptides, both at α- or ε-amino groups, and in a poorly understood but rapid modification of certain glycine residues.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] In pathology, acetone helps find lymph nodes in fatty tissues (such as the mesentery) for tumor staging.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] The liquid dissolves the fat and hardens the nodes, making them easier to find.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Dermatologists use acetone with alcohol for acne treatments to chemically peel dry skin.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Common agents used for chemical peeling are salicylic acid, glycolic acid, azelaic acid, 30% salicylic acid in ethanol, and trichloroacetic acid (TCA).
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Prior to chemexfoliation, the skin is cleaned and excess fat removed in a process called defatting, using acetone, hexachlorophene, or a combination of these agents.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone has been shown to have anticonvulsant effects in animal models of epilepsy, in the absence of toxicity, when administered in millimolar concentrations.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] It has been hypothesized that the high-fat low-carbohydrate ketogenic diet used clinically to control drug-resistant epilepsy in children works by elevating acetone in the brain.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Because of their higher energy requirements, children have higher acetone production than most adults – and the younger the child, the higher the expected production.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] This indicates that children are not uniquely susceptible to acetone exposure.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] External exposures are small compared to the exposures associated with the ketogenic diet.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone has a relatively long lifetime in the atmosphere of about 2 weeks.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Because of its long lifetime, it can be transported by atmospheric winds to the upper troposphere and lower stratosphere where it can influence hydrogen radical (HOx) production and ozone (O3) levels.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] These two peroxy radicals can then undergo a series of reactions to produce hydrogen oxide radicals (HOx) and can therefore have a significant impact on atmospheric chemistry including concentration of ozone (O3) in the upper troposphere.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Photolysis is just one possible processes that removes acetone from the atmosphere.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone can also be removed by ocean processes and by deposition to dry land surfaces.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] The contributions of each sink to the removal of acetone from the atmosphere is still not fully understood.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone's most hazardous property is its extreme flammability.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] In small amounts, acetone burns with a dull blue flame; in larger amounts, fuel evaporation causes incomplete combustion and a bright yellow flame.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] When above acetone's flash point of −20 °C (−4 °F), air mixtures of 2.5‑12.8% acetone (by volume) may explode or cause a flash fire.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Vapors can flow along surfaces to distant ignition sources and flash back.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Static discharge may ignite acetone vapors, though acetone has a very high ignition initiation energy and accidental ignition is rare.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone's auto-ignition temperature is relatively high 465 °C (869 °F); moreover, auto-ignition temperature depends upon experimental conditions, such as exposure time, and has been quoted as high as 535 °C.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Even pouring or spraying acetone over red-glowing coal will not ignite it, due to the high vapour concentration and the cooling effect of evaporation.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone should be stored away from strong oxidizers, such as concentrated nitric and sulfuric acid mixtures.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] It may explode when stored with chloroform in the presence of a base.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] When oxidized without combustion, for example with hydrogen peroxide, acetone may form acetone peroxide, a highly unstable primary explosive.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone peroxide may be formed accidentally, e.g. when waste peroxide is poured into waste solvents.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone occurs naturally as part of certain metabolic processes in the human body, and has been studied extensively and is believed to exhibit only slight toxicity in normal use.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] There is no strong evidence of chronic health effects if basic precautions are followed.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] It is generally recognized to have low acute and chronic toxicity if ingested and/or inhaled.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone is not regarded as a carcinogen, a mutagen, or a concern for chronic neurotoxicity effects.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone can be found as an ingredient in a variety of consumer products ranging from cosmetics to processed and unprocessed foods.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] The United States Food and Drug Administration rates acetone as a generally recognized as safe (GRAS) substance when present in food and drink at concentrations from 5 to 8 mg/L.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acetone is an irritant, causing mild skin and moderate-to-severe eye irritation.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Like many other solvents, acetone may depress the central nervous system at high vapor concentrations.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] Acute toxicity for mice by ingestion (LD50) is 3 g/kg, and by inhalation (LC50) is 44 g/m3 over 4 hours.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] In 1995, the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) removed acetone from the list of volatile organic compounds.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] In making its decision EPA conducted an extensive review of the available toxicity data on acetone, which was continued through the 2000s.
[src:astrobiology/acetone] It found that the evaluable "data are inadequate for an assessment of the human carcinogenic potential of acetone".
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Research in astrobiology comprises three main areas: the study of habitable environments in the Solar System and beyond, the search for planetary biosignatures of past or present extraterrestrial life, and the study of the origin and early evolution of life on Earth.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The field of astrobiology has its origins in the 20th century with the advent of space exploration and the discovery of exoplanets.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Early astrobiology research focused on the search for extraterrestrial life and the study of the potential for life to exist on other planets.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] In the 1960s and 1970s, NASA began its astrobiology pursuits within the Viking program, which was the first US mission to land on Mars and search for signs of life.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] This mission, along with other early space exploration missions, laid the foundation for the development of astrobiology as a discipline.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Regarding habitable environments, astrobiology investigates potential locations beyond Earth that could support life, such as Mars, Europa, and exoplanets, through research into the extremophiles populating austere environments on Earth, like volcanic and deep sea environments.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Research within this topic is conducted utilising the methodology of the geosciences, especially geobiology, for astrobiological applications.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The search for biosignatures involves the identification of signs of past or present life in the form of organic compounds, isotopic ratios, or microbial fossils.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Research within this topic is conducted utilising the methodology of planetary and environmental science, especially atmospheric science, for astrobiological applications, and is often conducted through remote sensing and in situ missions.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Astrobiology also concerns the study of the origin and early evolution of life on Earth to try to understand the conditions that are necessary for life to form on other planets.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] This research seeks to understand how life emerged from non-living matter and how it evolved to become the diverse array of organisms we see today.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Research within this topic is conducted utilising the methodology of paleosciences, especially paleobiology, for astrobiological applications.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Astrobiology is a rapidly developing field with a strong interdisciplinary aspect that holds many challenges and opportunities for scientists.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Astrobiology programs and research centres are present in many universities and research institutions around the world, and space agencies like NASA and ESA have dedicated departments and programs for astrobiology research.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The term astrobiology was first proposed by the Russian astronomer Gavriil Tikhov in 1953.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] It is etymologically derived from the Greek ἄστρον, "star"; βίος, "life"; and -λογία, *-logia*, "study".
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] A close synonym is exobiology from the Greek Έξω, "external"; βίος, "life"; and -λογία, *-logia*, "study", coined by American molecular biologist Joshua Lederberg; exobiology is considered to have a narrow scope limited to the search for life external to Earth.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The modern field of astrobiology can be traced back to the 1950s and 1960s with the advent of space exploration, when scientists began to seriously consider the possibility of life on other planets.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] In 1957, the Soviet Union launched Sputnik 1, the first artificial satellite, which marked the beginning of the Space Age.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] This event led to an increase in the study of the potential for life on other planets, as scientists began to consider the possibilities opened up by the new technology of space exploration.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] In 1959, NASA funded its first exobiology project, and in 1960, NASA founded the Exobiology Program, now one of four main elements of NASA's current Astrobiology Program.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] In 1971, NASA funded Project Cyclops, part of the search for extraterrestrial intelligence, to search radio frequencies of the electromagnetic spectrum for interstellar communications transmitted by extraterrestrial life outside the Solar System.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] In the 1960s-1970s, NASA established the Viking program, which was the first US mission to land on Mars and search for metabolic signs of present life; the results were inconclusive.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] In the 1980s and 1990s, the field began to expand and diversify as new discoveries and technologies emerged.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The discovery of microbial life in extreme environments on Earth, such as deep-sea hydrothermal vents, helped to clarify the feasibility of potential life existing in harsh conditions.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The development of new techniques for the detection of biosignatures, such as the use of stable isotopes, also played a significant role in the evolution of the field.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The contemporary landscape of astrobiology emerged in the early 21st century, focused on utilising Earth and environmental science for applications within comparate space environments.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Astrobiological research makes a number of simplifying assumptions when studying the necessary components for planetary habitability.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] These assumptions are based on our current understanding of life on Earth and the conditions under which it can exist.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] As our understanding of life and the potential for it to exist in different environments evolves, these assumptions may change.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Astrobiological research concerning the study of habitable environments in the Solar System and beyond utilises methods within the geosciences.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Research within this branch primarily concerns the geobiology of organisms that can survive in extreme environments on Earth, such as in volcanic or deep sea environments, to understand the limits of life, and the conditions under which life might be able to survive on other planets.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Emerging astrobiological research concerning the search for planetary biosignatures of past or present extraterrestrial life utilise methodologies within planetary sciences.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Scientists are using data from Mars rover missions to study the composition of the subsurface of Mars, searching for biosignatures of past or present microbial life.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Discoveries of surface and subsurface bodies of liquid on moons such as Europa, Titan and Enceladus showed possible habitability zones, making them viable targets for the search for extraterrestrial life.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] As of September 2024, missions like *Europa Clipper* and *Dragonfly* are planned to search for biosignatures within these environments.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Scientists search for signals from intelligent extraterrestrial civilizations using radio and optical telescopes within the discipline of extraterrestrial intelligence communications (CETI).
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] CETI focuses on composing and deciphering messages that could theoretically be understood by another technological civilization.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Communication attempts by humans have included broadcasting mathematical languages, pictorial systems such as the Arecibo message, and computational approaches to detecting and deciphering 'natural' language communication.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] While some high-profile scientists, such as Carl Sagan, have advocated the transmission of messages, theoretical physicist Stephen Hawking warned against it, suggesting that aliens may raid Earth for its resources.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Emerging astrobiological research concerning the study of the origin and early evolution of life on Earth utilises methodologies within the palaeosciences.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] This includes the role of water in the formation of the first cells and in catalysing chemical reactions.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The systematic search for possible life outside Earth is a valid multidisciplinary scientific endeavor.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] However, hypotheses and predictions as to its existence and origin vary widely, and at the present, the development of hypotheses firmly grounded on science may be considered astrobiology's most concrete practical application.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] It has been proposed that viruses are likely to be encountered on other life-bearing planets, and may be present even if there are no biological cells.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] As of 2024, no evidence of extraterrestrial life has been identified.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Examination of the Allan Hills 84001 meteorite, which was recovered in Antarctica in 1984 and originated from Mars, is thought by David McKay, as well as few other scientists, to contain microfossils of extraterrestrial origin; this interpretation is controversial.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Yamato 000593, the second largest meteorite from Mars, was found on Earth in 2000.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] At a microscopic level, spheres are found in the meteorite that are rich in carbon compared to surrounding areas that lack such spheres.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The carbon-rich spheres may have been formed by biotic activity according to some NASA scientists.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Hoover, a scientist with the Marshall Space Flight Center, speculated on the finding of alleged microfossils similar to cyanobacteria in CI1 carbonaceous meteorites in the fringe *Journal of Cosmology*, a story widely reported on by mainstream media.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] However, NASA formally distanced itself from Hoover's claim.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Most astronomy-related astrobiology research falls into the category of extrasolar planet (exoplanet) detection, the hypothesis being that if life arose on Earth, then it could also arise on other planets with similar characteristics.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] To that end, a number of instruments designed to detect Earth-sized exoplanets have been considered, most notably NASA's Terrestrial Planet Finder (TPF) and ESA's Darwin programs, both of which have been cancelled.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] NASA launched the Kepler mission in March 2009, and the French Space Agency launched the COROT space mission in 2006.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] There are also several less ambitious ground-based efforts underway.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The goal of these missions is not only to detect Earth-sized planets but also to directly detect light from the planet so that it may be studied spectroscopically.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] By examining planetary spectra, it would be possible to determine the basic composition of an extrasolar planet's atmosphere and/or surface.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Given this knowledge, it may be possible to assess the likelihood of life being found on that planet.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] A NASA research group, the Virtual Planet Laboratory, is using computer modeling to generate a wide variety of virtual planets to see what they would look like if viewed by TPF or Darwin.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] It is hoped that once these missions come online, their spectra can be cross-checked with these virtual planetary spectra for features that might indicate the presence of life.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] However, whilst the rationale behind the equation is sound, it is unlikely that the equation will be constrained to reasonable limits of error any time soon.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The problem with the formula is that it is not used to generate or support hypotheses because it contains factors that can never be verified.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The first term, ***R****, number of stars, is generally constrained within a few orders of magnitude.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The second and third terms, *fp*, stars with planets and *fe*, planets with habitable conditions, are being evaluated for the star's neighborhood.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Drake originally formulated the equation merely as an agenda for discussion at the Green Bank conference, but some applications of the formula had been taken literally and related to simplistic or pseudoscientific arguments.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Another associated topic is the Fermi paradox, which suggests that if intelligent life is common in the universe, then there should be obvious signs of it.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Another active research area in astrobiology is planetary system formation.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] It has been suggested that the peculiarities of the Solar System (for example, the presence of Jupiter as a protective shield) may have greatly increased the probability of intelligent life arising on Earth.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Biology cannot state that a process or phenomenon, by being mathematically possible, has to exist forcibly in an extraterrestrial body.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Biologists specify what is speculative and what is not.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Until the 1970s, life was thought to be entirely dependent on energy from the Sun.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Plants on Earth's surface capture energy from sunlight to photosynthesize sugars from carbon dioxide and water, releasing oxygen in the process that is then consumed by oxygen-respiring organisms, passing their energy up the food chain.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Even life in the ocean depths, where sunlight cannot reach, was thought to obtain its nourishment either from consuming organic detritus rained down from the surface waters or from eating animals that did.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The world's ability to support life was thought to depend on its access to sunlight.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] However, in 1977, during an exploratory dive to the Galapagos Rift in the deep-sea exploration submersible *Alvin*, scientists discovered colonies of giant tube worms, clams, crustaceans, mussels, and other assorted creatures clustered around undersea volcanic features known as black smokers.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] These creatures thrive despite having no access to sunlight, and it was soon discovered that they form an entirely independent ecosystem.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Other lifeforms entirely decoupled from the energy from sunlight are green sulfur bacteria which are capturing geothermal light for anoxygenic photosynthesis or bacteria running chemolithoautotrophy based on the radioactive decay of uranium.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] This chemosynthesis revolutionized the study of biology and astrobiology by revealing that life need not be sunlight-dependent; it only requires water and an energy gradient in order to exist.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Biologists have found extremophiles that thrive in ice, boiling water, acid, alkali, the water core of nuclear reactors, salt crystals, toxic waste and in a range of other extreme habitats that were previously thought to be inhospitable for life.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] This opened up a new avenue in astrobiology by massively expanding the number of possible extraterrestrial habitats.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Characterization of these organisms, their environments and their evolutionary pathways, is considered a crucial component to understanding how life might evolve elsewhere in the universe.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] While tardigrades are not considered true extremophiles, they are considered extremotolerant microorganisms that have contributed to the field of astrobiology.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Their extreme radiation tolerance and presence of DNA protection proteins may provide answers as to whether life can survive away from the protection of the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] In addition to their role as analogues for potential extraterrestrial life, extremophiles are also being investigated for their potential use in space biotechnology and in in-situ resource utilization (ISRU).
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Microorganisms capable of biomining and bioleaching, for example, could support the extraction of metals and nutrients from planetary regolith or asteroid material, contributing to sustainable human exploration.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Such applications highlight that astrobiology is not only concerned with detecting life elsewhere but also with harnessing biological processes to enable space exploration.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Tonietti *et al.* (2023) have discussed the relevance of biomining and bioleaching research within the broader framework of astrobiology and ISRU strategies.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Cockell *et al.* (2020) demonstrated in the International Space Station BioRock experiment that rare earth elements can be bioleached from basalt under microgravity and Mars gravity conditions, confirming that microbial metabolisms can operate in extraterrestrial environments.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Santomartino *et al.* (2022) outlined the principles of space biomining, including bioleaching, soil formation, waste recycling, and energy production, emphasizing the role of microorganisms as "the smallest space miners".
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] A subsequent review further developed a roadmap for sustainable space exploration based on microbial processes such as biomining, bioremediation, and biomanufacturing.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] More broadly, the concept of "applied astrobiology" has been proposed as an integrated framework that connects fundamental questions about life in the universe with biotechnological applications for human space exploration.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] In addition to extremophile research, quantum-chemical studies have shown that organic molecules produced by living systems generally display narrower HOMO–LUMO gaps than those formed abiotically, with this distinction sharpened among more water-soluble compounds.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Such gap measurements are thus emerging as a promising electronic biosignature for distinguishing biotic from abiotic chemistries in future life-detection missions.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Jupiter's moon, Europa, and Saturn's moon, Enceladus, are now considered the most likely locations for extant extraterrestrial life in the Solar System due to their subsurface water oceans where radiogenic and tidal heating enables liquid water to exist.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The origin of life, known as abiogenesis, distinct from the evolution of life, is another ongoing field of research.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Oparin and Haldane postulated that the conditions on the early Earth were conducive to the formation of organic compounds from inorganic elements and thus to the formation of many of the chemicals common to all forms of life we see today.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The study of this process, known as prebiotic chemistry, has made some progress, but it is still unclear whether or not life could have formed in such a manner on Earth.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The alternative hypothesis of panspermia is that the first elements of life may have formed on another planet with even more favorable conditions (or even in interstellar space, asteroids, etc.) and then have been carried over to Earth.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organic compounds ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic-aliphatic structure") that could be created naturally, and rapidly, by stars.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] More than 20% of the carbon in the universe may be associated with polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs), possible starting materials for the formation of life.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] PAHs seem to have been formed shortly after the Big Bang, are widespread throughout the universe, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] PAHs are subjected to interstellar medium conditions and are transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation and hydroxylation, to more complex organics—"a step along the path toward amino acids and nucleotides, the raw materials of proteins and DNA, respectively".
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] In October 2020, astronomers proposed the idea of detecting life on distant planets by studying the shadows of trees at certain times of the day to find patterns that could be detected through observation of exoplanets.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] David Grinspoon called astrobiology a field of natural philosophy.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Astrobiology intersects with philosophy by raising questions about the nature and existence of life beyond Earth.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Dunér has emphasized philosophy of astrobiology as an ongoing existential exercise in individual and collective self-understanding, whose major task is constructing and debating concepts such as the concept of life.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Persson also emphasized key philosophical questions in astrobiology.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] They include ethical justification of resources, the question of life in general, the epistemological issues and knowledge about being alone in the universe, ethics towards extraterrestrial life, the question of politics and governing uninhabited worlds, along with questions of ecology.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] For von Hegner, the question of astrobiology and the possibility of astrophilosophy differs.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] For him, the discipline needs to bifurcate into astrobiology and astrophilosophy since discussions made possible by astrobiology, but which have been astrophilosophical in nature, have existed as long as there have been discussions about extraterrestrial life.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Astrobiology is a self-corrective interaction among observation, hypothesis, experiment, and theory, pertaining to the exploration of all natural phenomena.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Astrophilosophy consists of methods of dialectic analysis and logical argumentation, pertaining to the clarification of the nature of reality. Šekrst argues that astrobiology requires the affirmation of astrophilosophy, but not as a separate cognate to astrobiology.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The stance of conceptual speciesm, according to Šekrst, permeates astrobiology since the very name astrobiology tries to talk about not just biology, but about life in a general way, which includes terrestrial life as a subset.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] This leads us to either redefine philosophy, or consider the need for astrophilosophy as a more general discipline, to which philosophy is just a subset that deals with questions such as the nature of the human mind and other anthropocentric questions.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Most of the philosophy of astrobiology deals with two main questions: the question of life and the ethics of space exploration.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Kolb specifically emphasizes the question of viruses, for which the question whether they are alive or not is based on the definitions of life that include self-replication.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Schneider tried to defined exo-life, but concluded that we often start with our own prejudices and that defining extraterrestrial life seems futile using human concepts.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] For Dick, astrobiology relies on metaphysical assumption that there is extraterrestrial life, which reaffirms questions in the philosophy of cosmology, such as fine-tuning or the anthropic principle.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The Rare Earth hypothesis postulates that multicellular life forms found on Earth may actually be more of a rarity than scientists assume.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] It provides a possible answer to the Fermi paradox which wonders: if extraterrestrial aliens are common, why are they not obvious?
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] It is apparently in opposition to the principle of mediocrity, assumed by famed astronomers Frank Drake, Carl Sagan, and others.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The principle of mediocrity suggests that life on Earth is not exceptional, and it is more than likely to be found on innumerable other worlds.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Research into the environmental limits of life and the workings of extreme ecosystems is ongoing, enabling researchers to better predict what planetary environments might be most likely to harbor life.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Missions such as the *Phoenix* lander, Mars Science Laboratory, ExoMars, Mars 2020 rover to Mars, and the *Cassini* probe to Saturn's moons aim to further explore the possibilities of life on other planets in the Solar System.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The two Viking landers each carried four types of biological experiments to the surface of Mars in the late 1970s.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] These were the only Mars landers to carry out experiments looking specifically for metabolism by current microbial life on Mars.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The landers used a robotic arm to collect soil samples into sealed test containers on the craft.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The two landers were identical, so the same tests were carried out at two places on Mars' surface; *Viking 1* near the equator and *Viking 2* further north.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The result was inconclusive, and is still disputed by some scientists.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Norman Horowitz was the chief of the Jet Propulsion Laboratory bioscience section for the Mariner and Viking missions from 1965 to 1976.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Horowitz considered that the great versatility of the carbon atom makes it the element most likely to provide solutions, even exotic solutions, to the problems of survival of life on other planets.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] However, he also considered that the conditions found on Mars were incompatible with carbon based life.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] EXPOSE is a multi-user facility mounted in 2008 outside the International Space Station dedicated to astrobiology.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] EXPOSE was developed by the European Space Agency (ESA) for long-term spaceflights that allow exposure of organic chemicals and biological samples to outer space in low Earth orbit.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The Mars Science Laboratory (MSL) mission landed the *Curiosity* rover that is currently in operation on Mars.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] It was launched 26 November 2011, and landed at Gale Crater on 6 August 2012.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The *Tanpopo* mission is an orbital astrobiology experiment investigating the potential interplanetary transfer of life, organic compounds, and possible terrestrial particles in the low Earth orbit.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The purpose is to assess the panspermia hypothesis and the possibility of natural interplanetary transport of microbial life as well as prebiotic organic compounds.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Early mission results show evidence that some clumps of microorganism can survive for at least one year in space.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] This may support the idea that clumps greater than 0.5 millimeters of microorganisms could be one way for life to spread from planet to planet.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] Mars 2020 successfully landed its rover *Perseverance* in Jezero Crater on 18 February 2021.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] It will investigate environments on Mars relevant to astrobiology, investigate its surface geological processes and history, including the assessment of its past habitability and potential for preservation of biosignatures and biomolecules within accessible geological materials.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The Science Definition Team is proposing the rover collect and package at least 31 samples of rock cores and soil for a later mission to bring back for more definitive analysis in laboratories on Earth.
[src:astrobiology/astrobiology] The rover could make measurements and technology demonstrations to help designers of a human expedition understand any hazards posed by Martian dust and demonstrate how to collect carbon dioxide (CO2), which could be a resource for making molecular oxygen (O2) and rocket fuel.
